post_text:
Camden Academy Senior, Lesslie Montiel, joined the prestigious 2020 MIT Online Science, Technology, and Engineering Community this summer! For this year's program, 'Redefine Possible', Lesslie chose "Mapping Justice - Designing Geospatial Tools for Social Change". With this topic in mind, Lesslie researched the correlation between poverty and education. A screen shot of her final presentation can be seen here.

Congratulations Lesslie, who was one of only 231 high-school students chosen for this program, on this remarkable effort!

post_text: Good afternoon, American Water shares important news to help residents beat the heat. The City of Camden opened two community pools and nine splash pad locations for public use. Residents are encouraged to take advantage of these free public water amenities and are strongly urged to refrain from turning on fire hydrants. Opening fire hydrants can make it very difficult for firefighters to keep residents safe, as it may cause a severe decrease in water pressure. Additionally, playing in the street where most fire hydrants discharge is dangerous for anyone but especially small children who may not be seen by incoming traffic. Let’s work together to keep cool and safe during these summer months by using the City’s pool and splash pad locations.

post_text: Just in case you missed the news regarding Covid-19 testing sites in Camden, the Courier Post shared information recently regarding the closure of the Camden Waterfront testing site and the opening of two new testing sites in Camden. One of the new testing sites will be located at 2600 Mount Ephraim Avenue, where the old county offices once were, and the other, opening Tuesday, will be located at Dudley Grange Park. Please note that East Camden has been identified by officials as a hot spot for the virus. Both new sites will offer walk-up and drive-through access; medical referrals are required. The Mount Ephraim testing site will be open from noon to 4 p.m., M-F; and the Dudley Grange Park testing site will be open from 8:30 a.m. to 4 p.m., M-F. Please read the article for more details.

Please feel free to share any ideas you are using that may be helpful to other families. Thank you!!

post_text: Congratulations 👏🏽 to the Camden Academy boys basketball team on a terrific season! Their record of 22-4, demonstrates the progress the team has experienced this season due to their dedication and hard work. Last night, Academy showed great athleticism in the 1st round of the South Jersey, Group 2 playoffs in Manchester. While the game was close during the first half, they lost to Manchester Township, ending their season for this year. We are proud of our players and appreciate the dedication of Coaches Phillips and Jackson.

post_text: Camden Academy Charter High School cordially invites you to join us to learn how students can best utilize their Camden Academy experience to prepare for college. Students and parents will have the opportunity to learn about pre-college programs, earning college credits as CACHS students, and the elements of a winning college application. This program is a must for students considering college and their parents. Light refreshments will be served. Please contact your student’s counselor or use this link to sign up: https://forms.gle/NzKboxJYSy6WbojKA

post_text: We are getting ready to kick off our 3rd annual holiday toy drive in support of the Kroc Center - Camden program, The Angel Tree! Last year we collected hundreds of toys from our teachers, staff, students, and community for Camden children. Our students deliver the toys and help set up the holiday toy shop at the Kroc Center.

post_text: At Katz Dalsey Academy, Ms. Burke's science class made back scratchers for the big smelly bear! This lesson is based on the book Big Smelly Bear by Britta Teckentrup. In the book, the bear can't scratch an itch on his back. To help the bear with his problem, our little engineers designed, built, and tested their own back scratchers! 👏 #Problemsolvers 👏 #STEAM

post_text: Camden Academy seniors volunteered at Restore, Habitat for Humanity (HFH), an organization that seeks to transform lives through decent and affordable home ownership. ReStore is the biggest fundraiser for the HFH affordable home ownership program. Our students organized and sorted rugs to make room for the next shipment. This is crucial as the more rugs sold, the more families served. It is estimated that the value of a volunteer is about $25.43 per hour. This number alone demonstrates just how valuable Restore volunteers are to HFH. We are so grateful to be able to partner HFH Restore.

Later this week they will use the seeds from the pumpkins to make pumpkin slime.🎃

post_text: Camden's Promise was at the National Constitution Center this past weekend as the Honorable Anthony M. Kennedy, Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States, received the 31st annual Liberty Medal for his efforts to preserve, protect, and defend liberty by inspiring Americans of all ages to learn about the Constitution through civic education and civil dialogue. The Liberty Medal was established in 1988 to commemorate the bicentennial of the U.S. Constitution. Given annually, the medal honors men and women of courage and conviction who strive to secure the blessings of liberty to people around the globe.

post_text: Camden's Promise National Junior Beta Club wanted to make a difference in the lives of people impacted by Hurricane Dorian in the Bahamas. Together, their fundraising efforts raised over $5,500. They then went shopping using the money raised to purchase materials for women and children in need of assistance due to the devastation left by Hurricane Dorian. The Beta Club's Hurricane Dorian Relief committee did a great job creating a budget, shopping list, and shopping itinerary. On Monday, October 21st, all the items were trucked to Florida and from there Carnival Cruise Lines will deliver the items to Freeport, Bahamas. Great job everyone!
